\section*{Solution}

We first find a multiple of \(5^{1000}\) which has no zeros in the last 1000 digits. Suppose that we have a multiple \(n .5^{1000}\) whose last zero is in place \(r\) (treating the last place as place 0 , the next to last as place 1 and so on). Then \(\mathrm{n}\left(10^{\mathrm{r}}+1\right)\) has the same digits in places 0 to \(\mathrm{r}-1\) and a nonzero digit in place \(\mathrm{r}\), and hence no zeros in places 0 to \(\mathrm{r}\). So repeating, we find a multiple n. \(5^{1000}\) with no zeros in the last 1000 digits.

Now let \(m\) be the remainder when \(n\) is divided by \(2^{1000}\), so \(n=k .2^{1000}+m\), and hence \(m .5^{1000}\) \(=\mathrm{n} .5^{1000}-\mathrm{k} \cdot 10^{1000}\). So \(\mathrm{m} \cdot 5^{1000}\) has the same last 1000 digits as \(\mathrm{n} .5^{1000}\). But it has less than 1001 digits, and hence it has exactly 1000 digits and no zeros.

